SIMPLE: respond
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Respond
<hw>Re*spond"</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*sp⟦ocr⟧nd")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Responded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Responding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>respondre</ets>, F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧pondre</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>respondere</ets>, <ets>responsum</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- +
<ets>spondere</ets> to promise. See <er>Sponsor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To say something in return; to answer; to reply; <as>as, to
<ex>respond</ex> to a question or an argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To show some effect in return to a force; to act in
response; to accord; to correspond; to suit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A new affliction strings a new cord in the heart, which
<qex>responds</qex> to some new note of complaint within the wide scale
of human woe.</q> <rj><qau>Buckminster.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To every theme <qex>responds</qex> thy various lay.</q>
<rj><qau>Broome.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render satisfaction; to be answerable; <as>as,
the defendant is held to <ex>respond</ex> in damages</as>.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To answer; reply; rejoin. See
<er>Reply</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Respond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Respond
<hw>Re*spond"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To answer; to
reply.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To suit or accord with; to correspond to.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For his great deeds <qex>respond</qex> his speeches great.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Respond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Respond
<hw>Re*spond"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An answer; a
response.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>A short anthem sung at intervals
during the reading of a chapter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A half pier or pillar attached to
a wall to support an arch.</def> <rj><au>Oxf. Gloss.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Respondency</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Respondence</ent>⟦br⟧
